[start section id="20103"]

Ms. Tilley is a pleasant 76-year-old female from Valley Stream who presents with the following oncologic history:
1.  March 2010 complained of abdominal pain for a month as well as rust-colored stools.
2.  April 1, 2010, colonoscopy was performed identifying a splenic flexure mass. Biopsies confirmed adenocarcinoma.
3.  April 2, 2010, CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis was negative for distant metastasis.  Chest x-ray was negative.
4.  April 16, 2010, taken by Dr. Moore for a segmental resection of the transverse colon.  Per the operative note, there was no evidence of distant metastasis.  Surgical pathology from the transverse colon identified a grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a 3.8-cm x 3.5-cm x 0.7-cm mass in the transverse colon invading through the muscularis propria with lymphatic and vascular invasion, and 1 of 16 regional lymph nodes was involved by metastatic adenocarcinoma.  Also, there was a separate 3.2-cm x 2.5-cm x 2.2-cm nodule present in the mesentery separate from the mucosal tumor.  There were negative surgical margins.
Mrs. Tilley presents to the Church Square Family Clinic for consideration of adjuvant chemotherapy for a stage III colon adenocarcinoma.  She has recovered well from surgery, although she is still trying to pack the wound at the umbilicus.  She has not had any exudate of drainage or blood from the wound.  She denies any fevers or chills.  She has lost about 20 pounds since April but has regained about 3 pounds over the past one-to-two weeks.  She has soft formed stools which no longer have the rust color.  She otherwise denies cardiac, respiratory, or genitourinary symptoms.  Denies any hematochezia for melena.

[end section id="20103"]

